    "hardcoded_aidar90s_042_msg" to "🚔 Local “authorities” offer a roof.\n10,000 ₸/month for protection.\n\nIf you refuse, there may be problems...",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_043_msg" to "🌍 The Chinese are looking for grain suppliers from Kazakhstan.\nContract for 500,000 ₸.\n\nBut you need a license and connections...",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_044_msg" to "🏦 The bank where you kept your money has burst!\nThe deposit of 100,000 ₸ was lost.\n\nThe state will not compensate...",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_045_msg" to "💒 Your wedding!\nThat one costs at least 200,000 ₸.\n\nBut this is important for family and status...",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_046_msg" to "🤫 The official demands a “gift” for permission.\n30,000 ₸ or things won’t move forward.\n\nPay or complain?",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_047_msg" to "📈 A stock exchange has appeared in Almaty!\nYou can buy shares of privatized companies.\n\nThe risk is huge, but so is the profitability...",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_048_msg" to "✈️ Relatives are leaving for Germany.\nThey offer to take you and your family.\n\nBut you need 500,000 ₸ for registration...",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_049_msg" to "🎆 December 31, 1999.\nYou survived the dashing 90s.\n\nWhat have you learned from this decade?",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_050_msg" to "📞 Father calls again.\n“You were right last time. But now it’s definitely safe! MMM-2\".\nThey want to take out a loan secured by an apartment.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_051_msg" to "📰 November 15, 1993 - the tenge was introduced.\nRubles are exchanged at the rate of 500:1, and in the queues everyone is discussing the same thing:\nsomeone saved for years, and now they are afraid that after exchanging old stocks\nAll that remains is the memory and the feeling that time has overtaken you again.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_052_msg" to "📜 August 30, 1995 - a new Constitution was adopted!\nPrivate property is protected by law.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_053_msg" to "🚨 RUSSIA DEVALVED THE RUBLE!\nThe crisis has hit Kazakhstan.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_072_msg" to "⚠️ CRISIS! Someone owes you money, but refuses to pay it back.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_073_msg" to "😮‍💨 Nerves are at the limit. Constant anxiety about the future.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_074_msg" to "⚠️ You have been living paycheck to paycheck for 6 months.",
    "hardcoded_aidar90s_075_msg" to "🎉 Annual bonus! You are doing great.",
    "hardcoded_story_001_msg" to "October 1993. Almaty lives in Soviet rubles, which almost no one truly respects anymore. Prices jump so quickly that people try to spend their salary on the same day: today it can be used to buy a bag of flour and meat for a wedding, in a week it may only be enough for the feast itself.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAidar is twenty-two. He is still too young to consider himself broken, and already old enough to understand: if the family does not hold on now, no one will come and put it back together. Parents saved money for years, dreaming of a calm old age and a new car, and now kitchen conversations increasingly sound the same: “they saved for life, but it turned out to be a couple of good tables and one very bad year.”\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nOn hand {capital}. Income {income}, if at all, will be paid in real money, and not in sugar or butter. Rumors are already spreading around the city that soon Kazakhstan will have its own currency and the old rubles will have to be changed in a hurry. And right now my father is calling: some people promise to return what they lost if they invest more. In the 90s, almost every hope comes to the house in a rescue suit. Aidar needs to decide whether to believe in her again.",
    "hardcoded_story_002_msg" to "The father hangs up almost with offense. In the 90s, people defend not only money that is no longer there, but also the right to believe that it can still be returned. It’s hard for Aidar to hear distrust in his own voice, but it would be even harder to remain silent.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAt work, there is also no feeling of ground under your feet. The bosses offer wages not in money, but in sugar, butter and something else that has not yet depreciated on the way home. The time is like this: everyone decides for themselves what is actually considered remuneration here.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nYou can take a product and turn it into an opportunity, wait for real money, or finally admit: survival requires looking for a second life outside of your main job.",
    "hardcoded_story_003_msg" to "Money disappears as quickly as the people who promised to return it. Everything is repeated with frightening precision: new faces, the same words, the same funnel of shame after the door has already closed behind the scammers.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe father can't stand it. His heart gives out before he has time to say anything useful or ask for forgiveness. One day, Aidar ceases to be just a son and becomes the main breadwinner of the family, although no one asked if he was ready for such a role.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nNow each next choice will be harder than the previous one. Because it’s no longer about personal ambition, but about who can keep the house from completely falling apart.",
    "hardcoded_story_004_msg" to "At a flea market, everything smells the same: dust, cheap plastic and a chance to jump out of poverty one lucky turn. Aidar is offered a shipment of Chinese watches, and the offer sounds exactly like almost all dangerous possibilities sounded in the 90s: quickly, confidently and almost believably.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThere are a lot of people around who have already stopped believing in a long, honest journey. Some sell shoes, some sell cigarettes, some sell other people's promises. Against this background, risk begins to look not an exception, but the only norm of the time.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nTo enter, you need to invest 30,000 ₸. For some this is a small thing, for Aidar it is almost a piece of the future. But if the party succeeds, for the first time he will feel not just survival, but upward movement.",
    "hardcoded_story_005_msg" to "The shipment arrives after weeks of nervous waiting. In the 90s, the expectation is almost always worse than the result itself, because during this time a person already manages to live both victory and collapse in his head several times.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe boxes stand in front of Aidar as a silent sentence of his insolence. Either this is the first honest chance to make money on your own courage, or another reminder that the market of that time does not love the hardworking, but those who have been lucky at least once.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThen you will have to quickly decide how exactly to live this outcome: with the dignity of a winner or with the harsh lesson of a person who tried to climb above his support.",
    "hardcoded_story_006_msg" to "November 1993. On the streets they talk about only one thing: they introduced the tenge. Rubles are exchanged at the rate of 500:1, there is a crush at the exchange offices, and people have that very 90s expression on their faces, when no one fully understands whether they are saving him or simply translating poverty into a new language.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nFor Aidar, this is not just state news. This is the moment when someone else’s story about “we saved for many years, and after the exchange there was enough for one good table” suddenly ceases to be someone else’s. If you make a mistake now, the mistake will cost not just interest, but entire months of your life.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nFormally, the country now has its own money. It feels like people still have the same old nerves. We need to decide how to survive the reform and what to do with the tenge immediately after the exchange.",
    "hardcoded_story_007_msg" to "December 1994. In the evening, the whole courtyard is glued to the TV: Grozny is shown on the news. There is someone else’s war in the picture, but in the 90s someone else’s misfortune too quickly becomes a common concern. In the kitchens they argue about who is right and who is wrong, but the average person is primarily afraid of something else: again the boys are sent to die, again the future sounds like an order, not a choice.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAidar has a cousin living in Russia. The mother asks to call the aunt, the neighbors discuss gasoline, borders and whether instability will spread further throughout the region. Even those who were not interested in politics now listen to the news with that special attention that comes when you understand that the world around you can fall apart faster than you can save up for the winter.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAn ordinary person cannot stop a war. But he can decide how to live with this news: hold on to loved ones, look for meaning in other people's experiences, or simply turn off the TV to save the remaining nerves.",
    "hardcoded_story_008_msg" to "The Afghan neighbor speaks quietly, without heroism. In war, beautiful words quickly disappear, all that remains is fatigue, hospitals and people who then find it difficult for years to live an ordinary life again. Aidar listens and for the first time notices how television news turns into everyday decisions: someone is afraid to take out a loan, someone is postponing their wedding, someone is hastily collecting documents to leave.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe war is far away, but anxiety has already settled in the yard. And yet there is a strange benefit in this conversation: when you hear a living person, the temptation to look at someone else's misfortune as abstract politics disappears. She always comes to someone's family and then casts a long shadow on everyone else.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nSometimes the important choice is not to win something, but to understand the price of stability in time and not confuse the noise of the TV with real power.",
    "hardcoded_story_009_msg" to "Spring 1995. In newspapers and in kitchens they are discussing that Kazakhstan is finally withdrawing nuclear weapons acquired after the collapse of the Union. For the world this is big politics, but for ordinary people it is a strange mixture of relief, pride and mistrust.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nSome say: “With a nuclear weapon, everyone would be afraid of us.” Others remember the Semipalatinsk test site, sick children, tired faces of relatives from those parts and answer more harshly: the country has already paid too much simply for the right to live next to atom. Aidar has never held anything more dangerous than a garage pry bar in his hands, but even he understands a simple thing of the 90s: the strength of a state is also measured by what it refuses to repeat.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nHe remains to decide what to do with this news in his head: be proud of the peaceful choice, regret the lost power, or try to understand how those who lived next to the test site feel, not on TV, but in real life.",
    "hardcoded_story_010_msg" to "An older neighbor recalls a trip to visit relatives near Semey: constant conversations about health, the habit of not asking unnecessary questions to doctors, and that special silence that happens in places where people have lived for too long next to an invisible threat. For Aidar, this story sounds stronger than any official speech.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nIn the 90s, money is almost always important, but there are things that neither dollars nor vouchers can buy: clean land, peaceful sleep for parents and the confidence that a child will not be born after someone else’s experiment on someone else’s fate. The story about the nuclear bomb suddenly becomes not geopolitics, but a conversation about the price of ordinary human life.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nSometimes growing up begins not with the first profit, but with the understanding that not every power is worth the price that ordinary families pay for it.",
    "hardcoded_story_011_msg" to "December 1997. The capital is moved from Almaty to Akmola. They laugh on the buses: who in their right mind would go to the steppe and the wind? But those who know how to listen to the era already feel something else: along with the capital, officials, construction, rent, new money and a new geography of ambition will be drawn there.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nFor Aidar, this is not an abstract reform. Each such turn in the 90s means an everyday question: where will the opportunities be tomorrow, which cities will begin to grow, and who will be the first to notice that the country is changing not only the address on the map, but also the direction of movement. Even if he doesn’t go anywhere himself, the era still moves the furniture in his head a little.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nYou can shrug it off, you can laugh, or you can take a closer look at the change as a rare moment when history has not yet been sorted out into ready-made conclusions.",
    "hardcoded_story_012_msg" to "The longer Aidar listens to conversations about Akmola, the more clearly he understands: big government decisions rarely look convenient at the moment, but almost always create a new market for those who do not laugh too early. Some will go to build, some to rent out apartments, some to open canteens and shops next to the new wave of bureaucrats.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nHe may not take off right now, but the thought itself is useful. In the 90s, it is not always the bravest who wins. Sometimes the winner is the one who notices a little earlier than others where life will flow and where prices, wages and other people’s hopes will begin to rise tomorrow.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nEven if this episode doesn't make him money today, it will leave behind an important habit: to look at the news not as noise, but as a map of future possibilities.",
    "hardcoded_story_013_msg" to "At the newsstand, people argue louder than the saleswoman. On the front page there is the dollar exchange rate, Chechnya, privatization, gasoline prices and another column about how the world after the Union is being reassembled, but without instructions. In the 90s, even buying a newspaper looks not like a habit, but like an attempt to at least grab onto something with the mind.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAidar notices how world news always comes up against everyday life. If there is a war somewhere, gasoline prices may rise again tomorrow. If there is a crisis somewhere, the familiar shuttle will disrupt the supply. If the state promises reform, in the evening people at home will again consider whether there will be enough money until the next payday. The big story here always turns into family math.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nYou can pass by, you can buy a newspaper for peace of mind, or you can linger and try to understand the era from these small conversations at the kiosk.",
    "hardcoded_story_014_msg" to "Inside the newspaper, everything is the same: reports about wars, notes about new borders, conversations about oil, the dollar exchange rate and another dispute about who now owes whom after the collapse of a large country. Aidar catches himself with a simple thought: the 90s were scary not only because of poverty, but also because of the feeling that the whole world seemed to live without railings.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAnd yet there is benefit in this reading. When you begin to see the connection between big events and your little life, it becomes a little easier to choose: whether to keep your money in dollars, whether to get involved in a dubious scheme, or whether to panic because of every new headline. Knowledge does not immediately feed you, but it often saves you from the most expensive stupidity.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe newspaper ends, but the era does not. But now Aidar at least understands better what kind of wind he has to live in.",
    "hardcoded_story_015_msg" to "2024 Asan leaves the office later than everyone else and catches himself with a stupid adult thought: the salary seems to be normal, but there is still no peace. Almaty is buzzing with startups, crypto, career leaps and other people's stories of rapid growth, as if the ordinary slow life here is no longer considered worthy.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nHe is smart, capable and already tired of his own impulsiveness. Too many times Asan tried to feel like a “real adult” through drastic decisions: buy, invest, accelerate sharply, prove. Almost every such breakthrough left behind not freedom, but new internal noise.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nOn hand {capital}. Credit card debt is 120,000 ₸, rent and life eat up most of the income. And it was at this moment that Dima calls with an offer that sounds like a quick way out of the eternal catch-up mode: crypto, x2 per month, “just don’t slow down.”",
    "hardcoded_story_016_msg" to "A month passed, and all the beautiful confidence collapsed into dry numbers on the screen. The crypt sank, Dima disappeared from the chats exactly when he became especially needed, and Asan had a familiar feeling rising inside him: anger at the market, at his friend, and especially at himself.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nHe feels uncomfortable not only because of the minus. He feels bad about how predictably he's once again bought into the promise of too-quick relief. Asan is not naive. He’s just tired of the slow path and every time he hopes that this time the rules will somehow be lifted just for him.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThere are 60,000 ₸ left on the exchange. And just now Dima returns with the classic remark of all unprofitable adventures: “It’s just a drawdown, we need to make it from the bottom.” The question is no longer about the market. The question is about Asan’s ability to get out of his own illusion in time.",
    "hardcoded_story_017_msg" to "The exchange turns out to be a dummy, Dima dissolves as if he never existed, and Asan is left alone with an unpleasant silence after his own mistake. Not the one they talk about later with irony. The one that really makes your body feel heavy when you open your banking app.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe loss of 150,000 ₸ affects not only the account. She strikes an image of herself as a reasonable person. And this is perhaps the most useful blow in recent memory. Because now the phrase “quick money” finally sounds less like an opportunity and more like a warning.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAsan still has time to collect himself like an adult. But then this will only work through the system, and not through beautiful hope.",
    "hardcoded_story_018_msg" to "The offer comes just when Asan has almost gotten used to his current life. The startup offers 700,000 ₸ and almost an advertising ticket to the next version of itself: faster growth, stronger team, less bureaucracy, more of a feeling that you are not a cog, but part of something real.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nBut he already knows the price of beautiful accelerations. Hiring from a bank is more boring, but predictable. It's louder, more interesting and more dangerous at a startup. For Asan, this is not just a career decision. This is the old internal fork between maturity and the urge to make a sudden leap.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe difference in money is big. The difference in risk quality is even greater. And you will have to choose not the person Asan wants to appear to be, but the person he really is today.",
    "hardcoded_story_019_msg" to "The first months in a startup feel like the right version of a career: real people, quick decisions, respect for brains, money that finally feels like recognition. Asan even begins to think that he has found the very pace at which he can grow without irritation.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nTherefore, the news that investors are not renewing financing hits especially meanly. Everything doesn't collapse dramatically, it just ends quietly. One week, a cool story becomes a line in the experience and the question: how exactly will he pay for life now.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe account has a cushion of approximately two salaries. This is enough not to panic out loud. But it is not enough to pretend that the solution has no price.",
    "hardcoded_story_020_msg" to "The senior offer comes not as a miracle, but as a quiet confirmation: all this time, Asan was still growing, even when he saw himself mostly as a mess, debts and chaotic attempts to speed up.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAlmost doubling your salary seems not only financial news, but also psychological. He's no longer the guy who's constantly dealing with the consequences of past decisions. At least for the first time he has a chance to stop being like that.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nBut higher income in itself has not saved anyone. Now the important thing is whether he can live this new level differently than he lived past increases and past hopes.",
    "hardcoded_story_021_msg" to "Financial freedom comes to Asan not with fireworks or a beautiful post on social networks. It comes in the form of one very simple thought: you can no longer make decisions out of panic. You may not grab any chance just because you are afraid to fall behind.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThe portfolio has grown, passive income has finally ceased to be a theory, and one’s own life has ceased to resemble an endless attempt to catch up with someone from the feed. This is perhaps the main victory: not only to save money, but also to grow a more resilient person within yourself.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nAsan collected capital and organized himself. For him it turned out to be the same route.",
    "hardcoded_story_022_msg" to "It is not life that ends here, but another version of Asan, who kept trying to jump over discipline. Bankruptcy is painful precisely because you can no longer invent comforting stories about yourself.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThere is no money, too much debt, stress has long become a background factor. But with failure comes a very stark clarity: many failures were not accidents, but the result of a habit of making decisions out of anxiety and greedy impatience.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThis is a tough ending. But there is one useful thing about it: now Asan knows exactly which version of himself should not be allowed to drive again.",
    "hardcoded_story_023_msg" to "The quietest failure looks like this: the salary comes, life does not collapse, but nothing really changes. Asan is no longer in crisis, but not on the route to freedom either.\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nThis is not a dramatic ending, but it is very recognizable. The man seems to have already gotten out of his stupid mistakes, but he still hasn’t put together a new system for himself. Every month flows away, and the future remains something that will begin “a little later.”\n\"\"\",\n\"\"\"\nFor Asan, this is an important lesson: the absence of disaster does not mean the presence of direction.",
)
